{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17653260","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17653260"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:44:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:44:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18567"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18567","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18567"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0,0.7,0.13,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11299"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114171"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11299","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11299"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18567"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96171"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10381"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26199"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26204"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114171","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114171"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary somatosensory cortex processes sensory information from different parts of the body.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the organisation of the primary somatosensory cortex?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Areas are mapped according to their proximity to the brain","Body parts are represented in alphabetical order","Regions are represented based on density of sensory receptors","Body parts are represented proportional to their physical size","Sensory representation is organised according to body parts with greatest movement"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary somatosensory cortex contains a \u003Cstrong\u003Erepresentation based on density of sensory receptors\u003C/strong\u003E. This creates a distorted map of the body (sensory homunculus) where areas with high tactile sensitivity like the lips and fingertips occupy disproportionately large cortical regions compared to less sensitive areas like the trunk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBody parts are represented proportional to their physical size\u003C/strong\u003E does not reflect the actual organisation, as the cortical representation does not correspond to actual body dimensions. \u003Cstrong\u003ESensory representation is organised according to body parts with greatest movement\u003C/strong\u003E relates to motor function rather than sensory processing, as the organisation is based on sensory innervation density, not motor function. \u003Cstrong\u003EAreas are mapped according to their proximity to the brain\u003C/strong\u003E has no bearing on cortical representation patterns. \u003Cstrong\u003EBody parts are represented in alphabetical order\u003C/strong\u003E does not describe the systematic pattern that runs from feet (medial) to face (lateral).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis organisation reflects the functional importance of detailed sensory processing for areas like the hands and face, which require fine tactile discrimination.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The primary somatosensory cortex is organised in a somatotopic map called the sensory homunculus.","Body parts with greater sensory innervation occupy larger areas of the primary somatosensory cortex.","The primary somatosensory cortex is located in the postcentral gyrus of the parietal lobe."],"references":["Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 48; pg. 604","Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96171"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18567"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96171","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96171"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-15T11:33:02+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-15T11:33:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11299"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114171"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","na